  "prompt": "Why does Audible.com take away all my credits when my membership expires? Didn't I pay for those credits last year?",
  "response": "When you purchase an Audible membership, you're essentially paying for the right to receive a certain number of credits each month, which can be used to purchase audiobooks. These credits are a part of the membership benefits and are not considered a separate purchase.\n\nWhen your membership expires, you lose access to the ongoing benefits, including the ability to receive new credits. However, any audiobooks you've already purchased with your credits remain in your library, and you can continue to access them even after your membership expires.\n\nIn essence, you paid for the membership, which included the credits as a perk, but you didn't purchase the credits as a standalone product. If you want to continue receiving credits, you'll need to renew your membership.\n\nTo avoid losing your credits in the future, you can consider the following options:\n\n1. Use your credits before your membership expires.\n2. Set a reminder to renew your membership before it expires.\n3. Consider purchasing a gift membership or a one-time audiobook purchase if you don't want to commit to a recurring membership.\n\nIf you have any further questions or concerns about your Audible membership, I recommend contacting their customer support team for more information.",
